      <div xml:id="NA300-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu vāyiṉ maṟuttatu. 2. varaivu kaṭāyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the door was refused. 2. It is also how marriage was urged for.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA300">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            cuṭarttoṭik kōmakaḷ ciṉanteṉa vataṉetir</l>
<l>            maṭattakai yāyaṅ kaitoḻu tāaṅ</l>
<l>            kuṟukā loṟṟa volki yāmpa</l>
<l>            ṟāmaraik kiṟaiñcun taṇṭuṟai yūraṉ</l>
<l>            ciṟuvaḷai vilaiyeṉap peruntēr paṇṇiyem </l>
<l>            muṉkaṭai niṟīic ceṉṟici ṉōṉē</l>
<l>            nīyun</l>
<l>            tēroṭu vantu pōtal collātu</l>
<l>            neyvārn taṉṉa tuyyaṭaṅku narampi</l>
<l>            ṉirumpā ṇokkaṟ ṟalaivaṉ perumpu</l>
<l>            ṇēer taḻumpa ṉūṇū rāṅkaṭ </l>
<l>            piccaicūḻ peruṅkaḷiṟu pōlave</l>
<l>            maṭṭi lōlai toṭṭaṉai niṉmē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The man from the village by the cool ghat,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the white waterlilies bow to the lotus,</l>
<l rend="indent4">become weak when pressed by the coming wind,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as if, confronted by the king’s daughter with glowing bracelets</l>
<l rend="indent2">being in rage,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ciṉant’ eṉa ataṉetir</term>: here we seem to face a double marking, one causal participle ("because/since the king’s daughter is in rage") plus a conjunction ("against this"). Is it just because simple <term xml:lang="ta">ciṉantataṉetir</term> would have been hypometrical?</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">the attendants to whom ignorance is befitting(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maṭam takai</term>: what is the nuance of <term xml:lang="ta">maṭam</term> here? Is it rather modesty (or even humbleness) than ignorance?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">were worshipping with [joined] hands,</l>
<l>he prepared [his] big chariot [with the words]</l>
<l rend="indent2">“the price [is she] with small bangles”(?)<note place="foot">Is this to be taken as a report of actual speech: the mission HE gives the bard is to persuade the lady? And the rest depicts the bard who has taken the chariot and come to HER house in order to fulfil his master’s order.</note>,</l>
<l>put [it] at our front-entrance [and] went [away].</l>
<l>And you,</l>
<l>having come with the chariot, without talking of going,</l>
<l rend="indent">as master<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">talaivaṉ</term> poses a slight syntactical problem. The context makes clear that it cannot refer to <term xml:lang="ta">Taṉumpaṉ</term>, so we have to relate it to the subject of the sentence, which means we would either expect a vocative, a 2nd sg., or at least an <term xml:lang="ta">āy/āki</term>.</note> of a folk of great tunes stilled by cotton as ghee overflowing,</l>
<l>touch the palm-leaf [thatching] our kitchen,</l>
<l rend="indent">as the big elephant bull going round for alms</l>
<l rend="indent2">there in the Ūṇūr of Taḻumpaṉ beautiful with [his] big wound,</l>
<l rend="indent3">[and] stand [there]!</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
